Here's a quick reference for the array methods I use every day.
## Transform: map
Transform every element:
```javascript
const names = users.map((user) => user.name);
// ["Alice", "Bob", "Charlie"]
```
## Filter: filter
Keep elements that pass a test:
```javascript
const adults = users.filter((user) => user.age >= 18);
```
## Find: find and findIndex
Get the first match:
```javascript
const admin = users.find((user) => user.role === "admin");
const index = users.findIndex((user) => user.role === "admin");
```
## Test: some and every
Check if any or all elements match:
```javascript
const hasAdmin = users.some((user) => user.role === "admin"); // true/false
const allAdults = users.every((user) => user.age >= 18);      // true/false
```
## Accumulate: reduce
Reduce an array to a single value:
```javascript
const total = orders.reduce((sum, order) => sum + order.amount, 0);

// Group by category
const grouped = items.reduce((acc, item) => {
  (acc[item.category] ??= []).push(item);
  return acc;
}, {});
```
## Flatten: flat and flatMap
```javascript
// flat: flatten nested arrays
[[1, 2], [3, 4], [5]].flat(); // [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]

// flatMap: map + flatten in one step
users.flatMap((user) => user.orders);
// All orders from all users in a flat array
```
## Sort: sort and toSorted
```javascript
// Mutates the original array
numbers.sort((a, b) => a - b);

// Returns a new sorted array (ES2023)
const sorted = numbers.toSorted((a, b) => a - b);
```
## Bonus: Object.groupBy (ES2024)
```javascript
const grouped = Object.groupBy(users, (user) => user.role);
// { admin: [...], user: [...] }
```
---
The chain `filter` → `map` covers most data transformation needs. Reach for `reduce` only when you need a non-array result.
